{{Infobox writer | name = Mary Lynde Craig | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Mary Lynde Craig.png | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Mary Delano Catherine Lynde | birth_date = {{Birth date|1834|03|24}} | birth_place = [[Vermont]], U.S. | death_date = {{Death date and age|1921|06|20|1834|03|24}} | death_place = San Francisco, California | resting_place = | occupation = writer, teacher, attorney, activist for women's property rights | language = English | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = | partner = {{marriage|Samuel Foster|1862}}; T. W. Hoffman (m. ?); {{marriage|Scipio Craig|1892}} | children = | years_active = | module = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Mary Lynde Craig''' (previously '''Mary Lynde Foster''', and '''Mary Lynde Hoffman'''; March 24, 1834 – June 20, 1921) was an American writer, teacher, and attorney. She owned property in [[San Francisco]], and was an activist for women's property rights.{{sfn|Simpson|2004|p=27}} Craig served as Associate Editor of the [[Redlands, California]] ''The Citrograph''. In 1893, she was one of four women practicing law in [[California]]. In 1891, she gave the "Address of Weicome" at the organization of Sequoia Chapter, San Francisco. While attending the National Editorial Association at [[Chicago]] with her husband, in May 1893, she also had opportunity to speak to other large audiences—once at the Auditorium, once at the Art Palace, and once at the Woman's Building.{{sfn|Simpson|2004|p=188}}{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239-40}} She served as president of the [[Pacific Coast Women's Press Association]] and historian of the Hastings Law column.
==Early years== Mary Delano Catherine Lynde was born in Vermont on March 24, 1834.<ref>{{cite web|title=California, San Francisco Area Funeral Home Records, 1835–1979: Mary L Craig|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNKG-WYF|website=FamilySearch|publisher=San Francisco Public Library, San Francisco History and Archive Center|accessdate=17 July 2017|location=San Francisco, California|date=20 June 1921|postscript=. From funeral home record book Vol. 10, H. F. Suhr & Co., San Francisco, San Francisco, California, p. 8301-8583}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1850 US Census: Springfield, Windsor County, Vermont|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HY-67S9-LPM?i=24&cc=1401638|website=FamilySearch|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|accessdate=17 July 2017|location=Washington, D. C.|page=460|date=20 August 1950|id=NARA Series M432, Roll 931}}</ref> Her parent were Aaron Phipps Lynde and Nancy Melinda (Walker) Lynde.{{sfn|Daughters of the American Revolution|1908|p=296}} She was of [[American Revolutionary War]] ancestry, descended from Lieut. Benjamin Lynde, of the [[Continental Army]].{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}}
==Career== Lynde moved to California in 1859 to take up a teaching post at the Lincoln Primary School on Fifth and Market Streets.<ref name="obit">{{cite news|title=Mrs. Mary Craig|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12434434/san_francisco_chronicle/|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]''|date=23 June 1921|location=San Francisco, California|page=4}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1860 US Census: 10th District, San Francisco, California|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:33S7-9YBF-9CM2?i=49&cc=1473181|website=FamilySearch|publisher=National Archives and Records Administration|accessdate=17 July 2017|location=Washington, D. C.|page=50|date=13 June 1860|id=NARA Series M653, Roll 67}}</ref> By the following year, she was working as the principal and teacher at Denman School.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Langley|first1=Henry G.|title=The San Francisco Directory|date=July 1860|publisher=Valentine & Company|location=San Francisco, California|pages=204|url=https://archive.org/stream/sanfranciscodire1860lang#page/204/mode/1up}}</ref> On February 1, 1862, she married Samuel Foster<ref name="cdnc.ucr.edu1863">{{cite news|title=Marriages|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18630101.2.17.1|accessdate=18 June 2017|work=cdnc.ucr.edu|agency=Sacramento Daily Union|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=1 January 1863}}</ref> with whom she had her only child, Samuel Lynde Foster (1863–1951).<ref>{{cite web|title=California Death Index, 1940–1997: Samuel Lynde Foster|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VP7Z-WY8|website=FamilySearch|publisher=California Department of Public Health Services|accessdate=17 July 2017|location=Sacramento, California|date=17 June 1951}}</ref> After Foster's death, in 1866, she moved briefly back to Springfield where she taught in the newly created consolidated secondary school,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hubbard|first1=Charles Horace|last2=Dartt|first2=Justus|title=History of the Town of Springfield, Vermont: with a Genealogical Record|date=1895|publisher=G.H. Walker & Co.|location=Boston, Massachusetts|oclc=246387498|page=114|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyoftownofs00hubb#page/114/mode/1up}}</ref> before returning to San Francisco to teach at Lincoln Grammar School and then later at San Francisco Girls' High School.<ref name="obit" /> When Foster's father died in 1872, her mother moved to San Francisco, where she taught in the Chinese Mission and lived with Foster.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harvey|first1=Margaret B.|title=Real daughters of the American revolution|date=1912|publisher=Guarantee Printing Company|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|pages=25–26|url=https://archive.org/stream/realdaughtersofa00daug#page/25/mode/1up/search/lynde|chapter=697. Mrs. Nancy Malinda Lynde|oclc=5722949}}</ref> Sometime later, she married Henry Fitz Warren Hoffman,<ref>{{cite news|title=Change in Name of Avenue Protested|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8554248/san_francisco_chronicle/|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]''|date=30 August 1918|location=San Francisco, California|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> a prominent businessman and benefactor of the city.<ref name="HFWH obit" >{{cite news|title=Henry F. W. Hoffman|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12435687/henry_f_w_hoffman_the_san_francisco/|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[The San Francisco Call]]''|date=29 December 1890|location=San Francisco, California|page=8|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>
Henry died in December 1890<ref name="HFWH obit" /> and in September, 1891 Hoffman entered [[University of California, Hastings College of the Law]].{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}} The reason she gave for entering law school at the age of 60 was to enable her to better support herself.<ref name="obit" /> On December 10, 1891, she gave the "Address of Welcome" at the organization of Sequoia Chapter, [[San Francisco]], thereafter serving as historian of the Chapter. About this time, she gave an address upon "Country Roads and City Streets," before the [[Pacific Coast Women's Press Association]], of which she was treasurer. This address was published by the Press Association as a monograph, and having been translated into Norwegian, was widely read in the US and in Europe. [[Scipio Craig]], president of the Editorial Association of Southern California, published the address, intact, in his paper, ''The Citrograph'', and sent greeting to its author. On November 12, 1892, at [[Vallejo, California]], they married.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}}{{sfn|Daughters of the American Revolution|1908|p=296}} She wrote for magazines and newspapers from New York to San Francisco.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}} At the time, she was the president of the Pacific Coast Women's Press association, historian of the Hastings Law column, and "a writer of note".<ref name="Newspapers.com1892">{{cite news|title=Marriage|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/47012385/|accessdate=18 June 2017|via=Newspapers.com|publisher=The Weekly Courier|date=19 November 1892|location=San Bernardino, California|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> In 1893, she was admitted to the California Bar, as only the second woman in California to practice law.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Clara Spaulding|title=California's Second Lady Lawyer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/12434526/honolulu_staradvertiser/|accessdate=17 July 2017|publisher=''[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]]''|date=10 February 1894|location=Honolulu, Hawaii|page=6}}</ref> She then returned to college to take the degree of LL.B.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}} Having taught for many years at the San Francisco Girls' High School, Craig retired in 1894.{{sfn|San Francisco municipal record|1916|p=95}}<ref name="obit" />
After her third marriage, Craig became the Associate Editor of ''The Citrograph''.<ref name="Tyler2007">{{cite news|last1=Tyler|first1=Betty|title=The fiery comet who brought Redlands its first newspaper|url=http://www.redlandsdailyfacts.com/article/ZZ/20070715/NEWS/707159940|accessdate=18 June 2017|publisher=Redlands Daily Facts|date=15 July 2007|language=en}}</ref> While in [[Chicago]], in 1893, Craig spoke to large audiences, including at the Auditorium, at the Art Palace, and at the Woman's Building.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239}}<ref name="SFCall1894">{{cite news|title=Its Congress to Open Up This Morning|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SFC18940213.2.113|accessdate=18 June 2017|work=cdnc.ucr.edu|agency=San Francisco Call|publisher=California Digital Newspaper Collection|date=13 February 1894}}</ref> Craig kept a home in San Francisco and [[Redlands, California]]. While a widow, she superintended the studies of her son who received a degree from Harvard College.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239-40}}
==Death and legacy== Craig died on 20 June 1921 at her home in San Francisco.<ref name="obit" /> The tens of thousands of dollars that writing and teaching had brought her, was spent on others.{{sfn|Collector Publishing Company|1893|p=239-40}} Hoffman Avenue in San Francisco was named for Craig.{{sfn|San Francisco municipal record|1916|p=95}}
==Selected works== * 1894, ''Is legislation needed for women? : an address ... read before the Woman's parliament of Southern California, Los Angeles, October 11, 1893.'' * 1901, ''Country roads and city streets : an address before the Pacific coast women's press association, July 18, 1901''
