{{multiple issues| {{more footnotes|date=February 2014}} {{Orphan|date=February 2014}} {{original research|date=December 2016}} {{POV|date=December 2016}} {{notability|Biographies|date=December 2016}} }} {{Infobox person | name = Mike Sharples | image = File:Sharples.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|12|14|df=y}} | baptism_date = | birth_place = [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], England | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1952|12|14|df=y}} --> | death_place = | education = | alma_mater = {{Plainlist| * [[St. Andrews University]] * [[University of Edinburgh|University of Edinburgh, Dept. of Artificial Intelligence]] }} | occupation = Technologist | years_active = | employer = | organization = | known for = human-centred design, evaluation of technologies of learning, application of studies of human cognition and social interaction to the design of novel interactive systems }}
'''Michael (Mike) Sharples''' (born 14 December 1952 in [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], UK) is a British academic working in [[Educational technology]]. He is a Professor of Educational Technology at [[The Open University]].<ref name="Sharples OU">{{cite web|last1=Sharples|url=http://www.open.ac.uk/people/ms8679|website=Stafflist|publisher=Open University|title=OUStaff}}</ref>
==Background== Sharples graduated from [[St. Andrews University]] in 1976 with a BSc. Hons in Computational Science, then moved to the Dept of Artificial Intelligence at the [[University of Edinburgh]] as a post graduate student. His PhD thesis was on the topic of Cognition, Computers and Creative Writing.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
==Career== Sharples held various academic appointments before becoming director for the centre for educational technology and distance learning at the [[University of Birmingham]], UK,{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} and later professor of learning sciences and Director of Learning Sciences Research Institute at the [[University of Nottingham]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}
==Research== Sharples' research focus is on adapting and developing new technology and socio-technical systems to facilitate learning, such as the use of mobile devices.
==Books== * Sharples, M. (1985) Cognition, Computers and Creative Writing, Chichester: Ellis Horwood. * Sharples, M., Hogg, D., Hutchison, C., Torrance, S., Young, D. (1989) Computers and Thought: a Practical Introduction to Artificial Intelligence. MIT Press. 406 pp. * Sharples, M. (ed.)(1993) Computer Supported Collaborative Writing. Springer-Verlag. * Sharples, M. & van der Geest, T. (eds.)(1996) The New Writing Environment: Writers at Work in a World of Technology. Springer-Verlag. * Sharples, M. (1999) How We Write: Writing as Creative Design. London: Routledge. * Littleton, K., Scanlon, E. & Sharples, M. (eds.)(2012) Orchestrating Inquiry Learning. Routledge. {{ISBN|0415601134}}.
